3gq.title: Ring
3gq.text:
[summary:
A ring $R$ is a triple $(X, \oplus, \otimes)$ where $X$ is a [3jz set] and $\oplus$ and $\otimes$ are binary [3h7 operations] subject to the ring axioms. It is standard to abbreviate $x \otimes y$ as $xy$. The ring axioms require (1) $X$ must be a [3h2 commutative group] under $\oplus$; (2) $X$ must be a [3h3 monoid] under $\otimes$; and (3) $\otimes$ must [distributive_property distribute] over $\oplus$.]

A ring $R$ is a triple $(X, \oplus, \otimes)$ where $X$ is a [3jz set] and $\oplus$ and $\otimes$ are binary [3h7 operations] subject to the ring axioms. We write $x \oplus y$ for the application of $\oplus$ to $x, y \in X$, which must be defined, and similarly for $\otimes$. It is standard to abbreviate $x \otimes y$ as $xy$ when $\otimes$ can be inferred from context. The ten ring axioms (which govern the behavior of $\oplus$ and $\otimes$) are as follows:

1. $X$ must be a [3h2 commutative group] under $\oplus$. That means:
   * $X$ must be [3gy closed] under $\oplus$.
   * $\oplus$ must be [3h4 associative].
   * $\oplus$ must be [3jb commutative].
   * $\oplus$ must have an identity, which is usually named $0$.
   * Every $x \in X$ must have an inverse $(-x) \in X$ such that $x \oplus (-x) = 0$.
2. $X$ must be a [3h3 monoid] under $\otimes$. That means:
   * $X$ must be [3gy closed] under $\otimes$.
   * $\otimes$ must be [3h4 associative].
   * $\otimes$ must have an identity, which is usually named $1$.
3. $\otimes$ must [distributive_property distribute] over $\oplus$. That means:
  * $a \otimes (x \oplus y) = (a\otimes x) \oplus (a\otimes y)$ for all $a, x, y \in X$.
  * $(x \oplus y)\otimes a = (x\otimes a) \oplus (y\otimes a)$ for all $a, x, y \in X$.
 
Though the axioms are many, the idea is simple: A ring is a [3h2 commutative group] equipped with an additional operation, under which the ring is a [3h3 monoid], and the two operations play nice together (the monoid operation [distributive_property distributes] over the group operation).

A ring is an [3gx algebraic structure].  To see how it relates to other algebraic structures, refer to the [algebraic_structure_tree tree of algebraic structures].

# Examples

The integers $\mathbb{Z}$ form a ring under addition and multiplication.

[fixme: Add more example rings.]
\[work in progress.\]

# Notation

Given a ring $R = (X, \oplus, \otimes)$, we say "$R$ forms a ring under $\oplus$ and $\otimes$." $X$ is called the [3gz underlying set] of $R$. $\oplus$ is called the "additive operation," $0$ is called the "additive identity", $-x$ is called the "additive inverse" of $x$. $\otimes$ is called the "multiplicative operation," $1$ is called the "multiplicative identity", and a ring does not necessarily have multiplicative inverses.

5m1.editSummary: linebreak between summaries to make them show up correctly
5m1.title: Irreducible element (ring theory)
5m1.clickbait: This is the appropriate abstraction of the concept of "prime number" to general rings.

5m2.title: Prime element of a ring
5m2.clickbait: Despite the name, "prime" in ring theory refers not to elements which are "multiplicatively irreducible" but to those such that if they divide a product then they divide some term of the product.

5md.title: Integral domain
5md.clickbait: An integral domain is a ring where the only way to express zero as a product is by having zero as one of the terms.

5mf.title: In a principal ideal domain, "prime" and "irreducible" are the same
5mf.clickbait: Principal ideal domains have a very useful property that we don't need to distinguish between the informal notion of "prime" (i.e. "irreducible") and the formal notion.

5mg.title: Unit (ring theory)
5mg.clickbait: A unit in a ring is just an element with a multiplicative inverse.

5r5.editSummary: removed empty hidden thing, best avoid dashing hopes of a proof
5r5.title: Principal ideal domain
5r5.clickbait: A principal ideal domain is a kind of ring, in which all ideals have a certain nice form.

5r6.title: Kernel of ring homomorphism
5r6.clickbait: The kernel of a ring homomorphism is the collection of things which that homomorphism sends to 0.

5r9.title: Ideals are the same thing as kernels of ring homomorphisms

5s5.editSummary: I couldn't quietly tolerate the intersection diagram being in front of the black lines while all the others were behind, I just couldn't
5s5.title: Operations in Set theory

5vj.title: Euclidean domains are principal ideal domains
5vj.clickbait: A Euclidean domain is one where we may somehow perform the division algorithm; this gives us access to some of the nicest properties of the integers.

5vk.title: Unique factorisation domain
5vk.clickbait: This is the correct way to abstract from the integers the fact that every integer can be written uniquely as a product of prime numbers.
